5:
Phew. Aaand we're done. All that's
left is to plate everything tomorrow
and then wait for the guests to
arrive, right?
9:
Correct. I'm looking forward to the
ball. Let's make sure it's a success.
13:
Right. Marianne's got a lot on her
plate, so we'll do what we can to
lighten her load.
16:
My apologies. Are you all right there,
Marianne?
18:
I'm all right, but... It's proper etiquette
to keep your eyes on your partner.
21:
I know you're nervous, but if your
gaze keeps wandering like that, your
partner's going to think you're eager
to end the dance.
23:
Enjoy the evening, sir. Leave any
possible complications to me.
25:
...So, what? Are you saying I should
focus on delivering empty
compliments and dancing? Just
leave myself as vulnerable as a
sheep to the slaughter?
27:
You hired me to handle the tough
stuff, didn't you?
30:
I know. It's not that I don't have faith
in you, but I can't help but worry...
33:
Please, put your mind at ease, sir. At
this rate, you'll exhaust yourself
before the ball even begins.
35:
Why not have a nice warm mug of
cider to soothe your nerves? It
sounds like you could use a rest,
anyway.
37:
No... My nerves are too wound up; I
wouldn't be able to rest if I tried.
Leave us be.
39: Oh, don't be like that sir. I only want—
44:
Who sent you? What are you doing
here?
46:
...What do you mean? I'm just trying
to do my job—
49:
Hmph. I remember the faces of all
the staff, but not yours. So I'll ask you
again. Who sent you here and why?
57:
Quick, somebody get some rope
and cloth!
63:
I knew it. I knew it... Nobody can be
trusted... nobody...!
69:
You knew someone has it out for
you—that's why you hired me. Now,
the more you can tell me about
them, the better I can protect you.
72:
I'm sure you've done your research
already. You know my background
and what kind of business I manage.
74:
Started your career from the bottom
as a mercenary, then worked your
way up the ranks. Your successes as
captain grew your troop into a
profitable security enterprise.
77:
"Security enterprise." Hah. I'm not as
grand as you make me sound. I'm
the same as you—a man who
sought a life off the battlefield.
79:
What you say is true. I secured
countless victories. Eventually, I went
from taking orders to giving
them—from what should have been
a safe, civilian home.
81:
You gained money, but not peace of
mind. A soldier can leave the
battlefield, but the battlefield will
never leave them.
84: That's what you're afraid of, isn't it?
88:
Some people targeted my wealth.

Some demanded I repent for my
sins.

And of course, some wanted me
dead.
89:
I wonder which category my
would-be assassin falls into. For
every victory, I made enemies. I
can't tell who's friend or who's foe
anymore.
91:
I understand. Truly, I do. But you
can't keep looking back over your
shoulder. You have to move forward
if you want to fulfill your—
93: You think I don't know that?!
95:
I know very well what you're saying!
But it's too much for me to bear... I'm
tired of living every day looking over
my shoulder, of jumping at every
shadow...
96:
...I think I'll retire for now. Please,
leave me be.
99:
I thought I'd find you out here. Are
you thinking about what happened
earlier today?
102:
...Yeah. I want to help, but there's
only so much I can do as a maid.
105:
I think he's one of the luckier ones.
He's come out of countless battles
unscathed, he can rub shoulders
with the elite, and his business is
flourishing to boot.
106:
On the flipside, there are those
who've been dealt a bad hand.
Some very unfortunate people even
end up dead.
107:
Whatever our circumstances,
though, we all have our battle scars.
Nobody has the right to put salt in
those wounds.
110: What do YOU think I should do?
113:
Follow your heart. You wish to help
him, do you not?
117:
Hmm... I think you should be honest
with him. Tell him where you're
coming from. I think that's the best
way to deal with the situation.
123: We've all got to start somewhere.
127:
True enough. I'll find Milord and bring
him back here. Thank you... both of
you.
131:
No problem. We'll get back to
prepping for the ball.
134: It will be the best ball ever.
136: I can't wait to see you dance.
